Figure 1: Neighbor inÔ¨Çuences areas.

Depending on spatial-temporal neighbor‚Äôs position, the Ô¨Åsh chooses between three behavior patterns: repulsion
- collision avoidance between Ô¨Åsh of the same group (turning the Ô¨Åsh‚Äôs orientation minimum-angle rotation so the
Ô¨Åsh‚Äôs orientation and that of its neighbor are perpendicular, Figure 2(a)), parallel orientation - the group moves in the
same direction (matching the Ô¨Åsh‚Äôs orientation with that of its neighbor, Figure 2(b)) and attraction - to maintain the
cohesion of the group to avoid predators (steering the Ô¨Åsh‚Äôs orientation towards its neighbor‚Äôs position, Figure 2(c)).

(a) Repulsion behavior pattern.

(b) Parallel orientation behavior pattern.

(c) Attraction behavior pattern.

Figure 2: Fish school behavior patterns.

Furthermore, the model should include a small random behavior in the searching phase for the selection of an
individual in relation to a set of them that meet the same conditions.
2.2. Prey-Predator Interaction
One of the main motivations of a Ô¨Åsh is to keep close to the group as a protective mechanism to avoid becoming
prey for a predator. When a Ô¨Åsh detects a threat, if it is part of the group it can increase the chances of survival, and
there are diÔ¨Äerent behaviors: dilution eÔ¨Äect - the prey change direction in order to confuse the predator and making
the prey selection diÔ¨Écult, confusion eÔ¨Äect - the predator will have diÔ¨Éculty in selecting a prey in front of a large
number of them [20], and many eyes hypothesis - the group size increases in order to have more eyes analyzing the
environment detecting potential threats.
As basis for prey-predator interaction we adapt two ‚Äùsteering behavior‚Äù routines [8] described below: pursuit
- to guide the individual towards a predicted target‚Äôs future position and evade - to guide the individual in opposite
direction of predicted target‚Äôs future position.
Moreover, we use a set of behavior patterns to eÔ¨Äective collective predator evasion [21] which consists of three
components: schooling, cooperative escape and selÔ¨Åsh escape and will be described below.

