2.2.1. Choosing a Rule
As the situation changes continuously around the Ô¨Åsh, each Ô¨Åsh needs to select an appropriate pattern to eÔ¨Éciently
avoid the predator. For this, the prey identiÔ¨Åes Ô¨Åve interaction areas with its predator (Figure 3).

non visible area
visible area
caution area
urgency area
capture area
Figure 3: Prey-predator interaction areas.

For the non visible area Ô¨Åsh will only consider the behavior in relation to its neighbors and this activity is called
schooling (the Ô¨Åsh only takes into account its neighbors‚Äô inÔ¨Çuence). If there is a threat in visible area, the Ô¨Åsh
performs schooling maintaining its speed in average speed (Table 1) It there is a predator in the caution area, the
Ô¨Åsh performs cooperative escape, (the Ô¨Åsh considers its neighbors‚Äô inÔ¨Çuence and uses evade to avoid the predator
without abandoning the group‚Äôs formation) and increases its speed to caution speed (Table 1). If there is a predator
in the urgency area, the Ô¨Åsh performs selÔ¨Åsh escape, (uses evade to avoid the predator‚Äôs trajectory, abandoning group
formation) maximizing its speed to maximum speed (Table 1). If there is a threat in capture area, the Ô¨Åsh is captured.
2.3. Avoiding Collisions
The movement detection sensors of the Ô¨Åsh are mainly the eyes and/or the body lateral lines that enable it to detect
objects in the environment that are relevant to its survival [22]. Using the information provided by these sensors, the
Ô¨Åsh can obtain every object‚Äôs absolute position in the environment: neighbors‚Äô proximity, potential collisions, predator
presence, etc. and the information provided by these sensors are limited by the maximum vision area (biological
characteristics and degree of illumination in the environment).
Collision avoidance is the Ô¨Årst behavior that should be implement and consist of three basic steps: obtain the
object visibility, detect the potential collision and avoid the potential collision. To determine the object visibility, it is
necessary to evaluate if the object is inside of the Ô¨Åsh‚Äôs visibility area, and if this is true it is necessary to evaluate if
the object is in the Ô¨Åsh path. Finally, if the object is in the Ô¨Åsh path, it is necessary to eÔ¨Éciently avoid the potential
collision.
2.3.1. Cylindrical Obstacles
On the basis that complex structures can be achieved from the union of simple geometric Ô¨Ågures, we consider
individuals‚Äô interaction with cylindrical obstacles. Cylindrical obstacles are deÔ¨Åned by the equation of a cylinder of
radius r with axis parallel to Z axis in the point (a, b, 0) (Equation (1)).
(x ‚àí a)2 + (y ‚àí b)2 = r2
